../../../beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-006/judgments/chain-03.md:23:This is a strong criticism. The proposed weak-type package is dominated by Calderon-Zygmund, interpolation, and endpoint singular-integral technology, which is exactly the territory the Tao filter makes suspect. The attack is also right that localization and nonlinear bookkeeping are more decisive than the weak-type versus strong-type distinction by itself, and that prior-art overlap needs to be screened earlier.
../../../beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-006/judgments/chain-03.md:33:The Tao screen and localization debt arrive too late in the original chain. For this branch, those are not downstream refinements. They are architecture-level admission tests. The added failure mode of "no mechanism, only endpoint packaging" is also correct and should be explicit.
../../../beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-006/judgments/chain-03.md:38:The attack is right that a theorem-like conditional statement can conceal circularity if its missing lemma is effectively the full problem, and it is right that the negative output may be genuinely stacked rather than narrowly single-cause. But requiring a theorem-like endpoint claim is still useful once the chain has already enforced mechanism, localization, and Tao screens. The refinement should therefore keep the theorem-like option while allowing stacked obstruction as the default honest negative.
